Docs.summary: The class contains the methods and properties that are used to send and receive the SOAP messages, set up Exchange impersonation, maintain user credentials, and identify the Exchange Web Services endpoint.

remarks.para: The class also contains methods for synchronous and asynchronous calls to the Exchange server. The class that is described in this topic was created by using wsdl.exe version 2.0.50727.42. The class that is created by using the Add Web Reference option from the Solutions Explorer pane of Microsoft Visual Studio 2005 is different. It contains a property named UseDefaultCredentials. If UseDefaultCredentials is set to true, the default credentials of the current user are used to make the Web service call. To use default credentials in a proxy that was created by using wsdl.exe, use the System.Net.CredentialCache static class to get the default system credentials and apply the credentials to the Credentials property of the class. There are additional asynchronous methods for calling the Exchange Web Services on the class that is created by using wsdl.exe. To view the differences, use a diff tool on the proxy files that were created by using wsdl.exe and the Add Web Reference option in Visual Studio 2005.
For an example of an asynchronous Web service call, see .

example.para: The following code example shows how to set up the class with credentials, the URL of the service, and Exchange impersonation. This example shows USER1 performing a FindItem call on the Inbox of USER2. USER1 is impersonating USER2.

Note: This example will run without the three lines that perform the Exchange impersonation. If these three lines are commented out, the example will search the Inbox of USER1. If these three lines remain in this example, Exchange impersonation must be configured for USER1.

Note: The Exchange server will return a 405 error if \ews or \ews\ is used for the endpoint instead of the full path of Exchange.asmx. By default, Internet Information Services (IIS) does not redirect requests to \ews and \ews\ to the appropriate Exchange.asmx endpoint.
